english:
  title: A Record of the Hall of Good Repose at Haein Temple on Mount Gaya in Silla
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the Royal Ordinances, the eastern peoples are called the Yi. Fan Ye wrote, "Yi means root—for the benevolent love life, and all things put down roots into the earth and emerge. Thus their nature is gentle and compliant, easily guided by the Way. The foolish are called Yi, for the term signifies harmony and ease, the method of teaching and transforming." In the Erya it says, "Going eastward to where the sun rises is the Great Plain. The people of the Great Plain are benevolent." The Book of Documents states, "Command Xi Zhong to settle in Youyi, called Yang Valley. Order the eastern plantings."

    Thus our Great Kingdom rises with sun and moon, thrives with their brilliance; waters flow smoothly and winds blow gently. Is it only the dormant things that stir to life again? Nay—new shoots burst forth in abundance, growth itself taking root in the East. Moreover, the Book of Poetry speaks of "gazing westward," while the Buddha took his first eastern step. Thus should the eastern peoples strive to take refuge in the Three Treasures. Such is the nature of the land, which Heaven itself provides.

    The Analects say: "Above, he does not serve the Son of Heaven; below, he does not serve the feudal lords. With reverence and stillness he honors breadth; through broad learning he knows restraint." The Change likewise speaks of "not serving kings and princes, exalting one's own affairs," and "the hermit living rightly attains good fortune." How then does one who dwells hidden and walks the Way not receive the Buddha's name? This is merely to use Confucian words to illumine the Buddhist path—the same then as now.

    How splendid! What Heaven treasures is humanity; what humanity honors is the Way. When people amplify the Way, the Way does not distance itself from people. When the Way is elevated, people naturally become precious. What can aid the Way? Only the ennoblement of virtue. Thus in honoring the Way and treasuring virtue, we turn to the foremost of dharmas. Only then do we accord with the workings of things. We must rectify names to speak of great virtue—the Way strengthened, the name magnified, virtue perfected and ascending.

    The Rites teach: "To gain position, gain name, gain longevity." Is not this the doctrine of transformation? The Eastern lands took but part of this meaning. Investigating the roots of such practice, I find it recorded in the Record of Seasonal Customs of Jingchu by the Child Scholar of Liang: "Long ago, when the Lord Sun Quan of Wu lay gravely ill, the Daoist Ge Xuan came to visit. Those in Sun's household heard a voice from the void saying, 'Seeing that a Great Virtue Daoist is present, this should be reported.' Thus the title Great Virtue was established."

    Later, when Buddhist scriptures were translated and verses collected, such great virtues as Shariputra and his kindred became numerous. The Three Realms Master entrusted the upholding of dharma to princes and ministers—how profound the intent! Why is this? To transform customs requires honoring the worthy. It is harder to tame a tiger than to love a dragon. Thus those who govern nations strive to make the dharma flourish, that its light exceed even a held torch. So they elevate pure names and reveal remarkable places.

    Long ago, our Queen Sondok appeared as if the embodiment of auspiciousness itself—though she ruled as Eastern sovereign, she gazed toward the Western Buddha-dharma. At that time came visiting monks: Jiying and Senggu, who journeyed to the red waters and returned to illuminate the blue hills. Their higher path was cherished, and they were raised to the rank of Great Virtue. Thereafter the followers multiplied. The talented of the Five Sacred Mountains all strived to reach the mountain's heights; the Buddhist seed throughout the four seas equally bore the name of those who entered the sea.

    There were the Yoga, the Skandhaka, the Vinaya, the Abhidharma. There were those like Qi Zhou who gathered in motley colors—some recommended by recitation, some selected for their mnemonic power, some appointed for their eloquence, some rewarded for their austere discipline. All were chosen and elevated by royal decree, bearing heavy golden plaques as if contained in the imperial net, their radiance fused with jade temples. To employ them was like striking fire from flint, like selecting timber from the mountain. One hoped to sacrifice oneself without ever breaking the bounds of age. Thus did one cross beyond the years of Wei Yuan's awakening and reach the age when Confucius studied the Changes. Only then was one permitted to ascend this seat, the term set for seven years.

    When practice is sincere and mind nimble, when virtue becomes sage-like, one receives a special honor and remarkable epithet to bring glory to the rising generation. Thus the young who perfect their studies tenfold are like the udumbara flower blooming once. This belongs to the Mahayana and Samadhana schools. In stillness, one possesses the refined essence of the Mountain King; in motion, the majestic grandeur of the Ocean Assembly—as if flying through the nine heavens or treading with the single horn of the qilin.

    Within the temple, one meets as if encountering the incarnate Buddha; within the hall, one venerates as if honoring a stern father. Though all crowd forward with eager elbows, each command falls like a glance. Yet all maintain pristine conduct, and arrogance is rarely seen. Is this not what is meant by "lofty yet without peril, dignified yet not fierce"? Moreover, those who master their studies lecture well; their words become teachers. When pestles thunder and incense-smoke billows, they gaze upon the Three Treasures with ease and regard the four congregations without clamor.

    From caves the elephant-king emerges, treading its measured steps; upon the seat the lion roars its solemn voice. Heaven's gate holds clouds, the sea's lip churns waves. Just as a divine awl contests its sharpness, so does a clear mirror forget its weariness. When questioned, all receive answers; no doubt goes unresolved. The arrogant lose their bearing; those who sought favor learn to turn back. Always self-possessed, one fears nothing; wishing to conceal one's gifts, one cannot. Who said "he who wrongs me is my enemy"? This accords with "in righteous action, one yields to none."

    In guiding people, custom is awakened thereby; in protecting the nation, the Way flourishes thereby. The Sutra teaches: "To receive and uphold the ten-thousand-verse scripture is not equal to grasping a single sentence's meaning." Thus "the one who comes later arrives first"—this mountain is what is meant. Why? The patriarch Suneung the Great Virtue practiced under Master Shenlin, crossed to the Middle Kingdom in the beginning of the Dali era, dwelt in a hollow tree forgetting the body, sought the hermit-perfected on the mountain and gained the marrow. He exhausted the ocean of doctrine and plumbed the depths of Chan, then returned to his homeland to receive luminous selection.

    He sighed: "People must cultivate learning; the world treasures storing wealth. Already possessing Heaven-Earth's refined essence, having received the mountains and rivers' beauty—yet the bird chooses its tree; shall I not clear my patch?" In the eighteenth year of Zhenyuan, on the sixteenth day of the tenth month, he gathered like-minded companions and established this dwelling. The mountain spirit blessed the name "Wondrous Virtue"; the land embraced the form of "Cool Radiance." Five crests were arrayed; a single hair competed to be plucked.

    At this time the Great Queen of Seondeok reigned as mother to the four quarters and nurtured the three schools as children. Hearing this, she rejoiced with reverence, vowed her allegiance on an appointed day, and offered fine vegetables accompanied by silk tributes—thus receiving Heaven's blessing through earthly accord. Yet as disciples gathered like mist at the gate, the master suddenly departed. The Chan Master Riben succeeded him, bearing the torch of accomplishment.

    Following the Mean, he perfected the temple's governance; drawing from the Great Mighty, he adorned the constructions. Cloud-like spires rose; mist-like eaves spread. Day by day renewed, month by month transformed. Thus Mount Gaya's realm became a fit foundation for enlightenment; the precious seal of Ocean-Imprint shone with surpassing worth.

    The overgrown woods were all cleared—as if pearls adorning an inexhaustible shore. Though only a hundred years have passed since clearing the ground, those who manifested themselves embody all the virtues. Five came together in reciting; three opened the dharma-hall. All maintain accord between word and deed, between name and reality. The Documents say: "Neglecting small things, one finally harms great virtue." How then could we step beyond our bounds?

    The high mountain receives even dust and stands lofty; the humble stream spurns no trickle and reaches the sea. Yet beware—the wave that rushes forth with all may drown itself. Though sustenance depends on earth's provisions, the cultivation of mind depends solely on ennobling virtue. Having committed ourselves to the Buddha-dharma, why not illuminate the traces of the bird? So we resolved to adorn the temple, adding luster to the blue peaks.

    May those who enter find the hall aligned with dharma, and those who sit facing the wall find meditation secure. When one is diligent, fruit follows; when one departs, one does not perish. The record is here—how could those who follow not exert themselves?

    Written in the twelfth month on the final day of the third year of Guanghua of Great Tang, in the season of the Heavenly Unity Great Fast.
