    - Queen Sondok (善德女王) of Silla (r. 632-647) was indeed one of ancient Korea's most notable rulers and a devoted patron of Buddhism.
    - The patriarch Suneung is identified with the historical Buddhist monk who lived in the Tang dynasty and later established Haein Temple on Mount Gaya.
    - The seven-year probationary period and various other monastic regulations mentioned reflect the formal structures of Korean Buddhist monastery governance.
    - The "Zhenyuan eighteenth year" corresponds to 802 CE, marking the traditional founding date of Haein Temple.
